  <li><strong>Serve Reds Slightly Chilled for Thanksgiving</strong> - Traditional Thanksgiving reds like Pinot Noir, Beaujolais, and light Zinfandels should be served at 60-65°F rather than room temperature. The slight chill enhances their natural acidity, which is crucial for cutting through rich gravies and butter-laden sides while preventing the alcohol from overwhelming delicate turkey flavors.</li>

  <li><strong>Choose High-Acid Wines for Cranberry Sauce Harmony</strong> - The tartness of cranberry sauce can make low-acid wines taste flat and flabby. Opt for naturally high-acid varieties like Riesling, Sauvignon Blanc, or Barbera d'Alba. The wine's acidity will complement rather than clash with the cranberries, creating a harmonious bridge between sweet and savory dishes.</li>

  <li><strong>Decant Older Reds 2-3 Hours Before Thanksgiving Dinner</strong> - If serving aged Burgundy, older Barolo, or mature Cabernet Sauvignon with your feast, decant them mid-afternoon. This extended aeration time allows the wine's complex tertiary flavors to fully develop, ensuring they can stand up to the aromatic complexity of sage stuffing, roasted root vegetables, and herb-rubbed turkey.</li>

  <li><strong>Use Burgundy Glasses for Thanksgiving Pinot Noir</strong> - The large bowl of Burgundy glasses concentrates the delicate red fruit and earthy aromas of Pinot Noir, which are essential for pairing with turkey's subtle flavors. Standard red wine glasses are too narrow and will mute the wine's nuanced character that makes it perfect for this traditional pairing.</li>

  <li><strong>Avoid Wines Aged in Heavy Oak for Thanksgiving</strong> - Skip heavily oaked Chardonnays or big, oaky Cabernets on Thanksgiving. The vanilla and spice notes from oak aging compete with the herbs, spices, and aromatics already present in traditional Thanksgiving dishes. Instead, choose wines with minimal oak influence or those aged in neutral vessels to let both food and wine shine.</li>

  <li><strong>Open Champagne or Sparkling Wine Just Before Appetizers</strong> - The bubbles and crisp acidity of sparkling wine cleanse the palate between rich appetizers and the main meal. Open bottles right before serving to maintain optimal effervescence - the bubbles help lift heavy flavors and prepare your guests' palates for the wine transitions throughout the meal.</li>

  <li><strong>Plan Wine Progression from Light to Medium-Bodied</strong> - Start with lighter aperitif wines like Chablis or Sancerre, move to medium-bodied options like Oregon Pinot Noir or white Rhône blends with the main course, and finish with slightly richer dessert wines like late-harvest Riesling with pumpkin pie. This progression prevents palate fatigue and ensures each wine tastes its best throughout the lengthy Thanksgiving meal.</li>
</ol>

  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
<div class="space-y-6">
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine pairs best with turkey and gravy?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Pinot Noir is the classic choice, as its bright acidity and earthy undertones complement turkey's mild flavor while cutting through rich gravy. For white wine lovers, a full-bodied Chardonnay or Viognier provides enough weight to match the dish's richness. The key is choosing wines with enough structure to stand up to savory herbs like sage and thyme without overwhelming the delicate turkey meat.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve different wines with different Thanksgiving dishes?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">While you can serve multiple wines, it's more practical to choose one versatile wine that complements the entire meal. Look for wines with balanced acidity and moderate tannins—like Côtes du Rhône, Grenache, or German Riesling—that work with both savory mains and sweet sides. If serving multiple wines, limit yourself to 2-3 selections: a light red, a medium-bodied white, and perhaps a dessert wine for pumpkin pie.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">How much wine should I buy for Thanksgiving dinner?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Plan for one bottle per two guests for a 3-4 hour dinner, accounting for the leisurely pace of Thanksgiving meals. Since people often drink more during holiday gatherings, consider buying 25% extra beyond this baseline. For a table of 8, purchase 5-6 bottles, mixing 60% red wines and 40% white to accommodate different preferences throughout the meal.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make with Thanksgiving wine pairing?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is choosing wines that are too heavy or tannic, which clash with Thanksgiving's sweet elements like cranberry sauce and sweet potatoes. Big Cabernets or oaky Chardonnays often overpower the meal's delicate balance of savory and sweet flavors. Instead, focus on food-friendly wines with bright acidity and restrained oak that enhance rather than compete with the diverse flavors on your plate.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic alternatives that still pair well with Thanksgiving food?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sparkling apple cider, pomegranate juice with soda water, and grape juice blends offer excellent pairing potential with Thanksgiving flavors. These beverages provide the acidity and fruit-forward character that complement turkey and sides without alcohol. For a more sophisticated option, try non-alcoholic sparkling wines or dealcoholized Pinot Noir, which maintain wine-like complexity while offering the same food-pairing benefits.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What temperature should I serve Thanksgiving wines?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Serve light reds like Pinot Noir slightly chilled at 60-65°F to enhance their bright, food-friendly character, while whites should be well-chilled at 45-50°F. Remove red wines from the fridge 15-20 minutes before serving if you've chilled them. This temperature approach prevents wines from tasting heavy or alcoholic, maintaining the fresh, celebratory feel that matches Thanksgiving's festive atmosphere.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair wine with pumpkin pie and other Thanksgiving desserts?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sweet dessert wines like Moscato d'Asti, late-harvest Riesling, or tawny Port pair beautifully with pumpkin pie's spiced, creamy texture. The wine's sweetness should match or exceed the dessert's sweetness to avoid tasting sour. For lighter options, try sparkling Moscato with apple pie or a glass of cream sherry with pecan pie—the nutty, caramel notes create perfect harmony with traditional Thanksgiving sweets.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Thanksgiving wine pairing suitable for wine beginners?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—Thanksgiving offers an ideal introduction to wine pairing because the meal's familiar, comfort-food flavors make it easy to notice how wine enhances food. Start with crowd-pleasing options like Beaujolais, Pinot Grigio, or off-dry Riesling that offer clear food-pairing benefits without overwhelming complexity. The relaxed, family-friendly atmosphere also removes pressure, allowing beginners to experiment and learn what they enjoy most.</p>
  </div>
